His research interests include French social history in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, and French and European intellectual and political history since World War II. A frequent contributor to many journals in Europe, the U.S., and the Middle East, Judt is also the author or editor of 14 books, including his latest work, Ill Fares the Land . His Postwar: A History of Europe since 1945 (2005), which the New York Times named as one of the "10 Best Books of 2005," has been translated into 19 languages and was awarded the European Book Prize.     A frequent contributor to the New York Review of Books , the New York Times , and many journals in Europe, the U.S., and the Middle East, Judt was awarded Britain’s Orwell Prize for Lifetime Achievement in 2009 and the Hannah Arendt Prize in 2007.     "Even in a rich field of brilliant historians, the name of Tony Judt stands out," the Orwell Prize selection committee said in its April 2009 announcement. "But like other great historians before him he has also engaged in public debate, becoming a politicologue …and controversialist, whose essays, largely in the New York Review of Books, have been distinguished by their intelligence, insight and conspicuous courage."     In 2008, he was named to Foreign Policy's "Top 100 Public Intellectuals" list.        After teaching in Cambridge, Oxford (1972-1978), and the University of California at Berkeley (1978-1980), Judt came to NYU in 1987, with appointments in the Department of History and NYU’s Institute of French Studies. While at NYU, he also served as chair of the History Department (1992-1993) and dean for humanities (1993-1995). Beginning in 2006, Judt held the title of University Professor, a rank conferred upon outstanding NYU faculty whose scholarship extends across traditional disciplinary boundaries and who are internationally recognized scholars and teachers.   Judt serves as the director of NYU’s Remarque Institute, which was established in 1995. Its purpose is to support and promote the study and discussion of Europe and to encourage and facilitate communication between Americans and Europeans. The Institute, named after author Erich Maria Remarque ( All Quiet on the Western Front ), was established from a bequest from Remarque’s widow, actress Paulette Goddard.     Born January 2, 1948, Judt received a bachelor of arts degree from Cambridge University’s King’s College in 1969 and a Ph.D. in 1973. Judt, who also attended the École Normale Supérieure, Paris, was a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the British Academy.     He delivered the lecture, "Disturbing the Peace: Intellectuals and Universities in an Illiberal Age," as part of the University Professorship Lecture series. A History of Europe since 1945       by Tony Judt     Published in October 2005 by Penguin (US) and Heinemann (UK)      The literature on Europe since the Second World War is huge - and like  Europe itself - steadily expanding. The titles listed in this  bibliography are but a small selection of the English-language books  that I have found most interesting or helpful in the writing of Postwar .  Wherever possible I have listed books (and editions of books) that are  likely to be available for readers to consult or purchase. For the same  reason I have not included primary sources except memoirs and the  occasional contemporary report, nor have I listed published works in  other languages.   The bibliography is arranged in three parts. The first section is a  list of books dealing with the history of modern Europe, together with  works devoted to particular countries or regions. The second section is  divided into a number of general topics: the Cold War, immigration,  culture and the arts, etc. In the third section I have grouped books by  chapter, listing works to which I am indebted for information used in a  particular chapter or that I found especially helpful.   This way of organizing the bibliography inevitably entails overlap.  Thus, to take one example: readers interested in learning more about  French intellectuals in the Cold War years might refer to books listed  under various headings - France; The Cold War; Europe and the USA; Intellectuals; as well as e.g. Chapter VII: Culture Wars . Similarly, readers seeking to learn more about the economic history of post-war Europe might find it helpful to look under General Histories; Economics; European Union , as well as various chapters where economic history is emphasized, notably Chapters III, X, XIV , etc. Like Postwar   itself, this bibliography is intended for the general reader, though I  hope that students and specialists will also find it a useful guide.
